{"title_page": "Jesu Leiden, Pein und Tod", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = \"{{lang|de|Jesu Leiden, Pein und Tod|italic=no}}\"\n| type                = [[Lutheran]] [[Passion hymn]]\n| composer            = \n| image               = \n| image_upright       = \n| caption             = \n| translation         = \n| text                = by [[Paul Stockmann]]\n| language            = German\n| melody              = by [[Melchior Vulpius]]\n| composed            = <!--{{Start date|1533}}-->\n| published           = {{Start date|1633}}\n}}\n\"'''{{lang|de|Jesu Leiden, Pein und Tod|italic=no}}'''\" is a German [[Lutheran hymn]] by [[Paul Stockmann]]. Written in 34 stanzas and published in 1633, it narrates the [[Passion of Jesus]]. It was sung to a melody [[Melchior Vulpius]]. \n[[Johann Sebastian Bach]] used three of its stanzas as [[chorale]]s in his ''[[St John Passion]]''.\n\n== History ==\n[[Paul Stockmann]] wrote 34 stanzas of eight lines each, rhyming ABABCDCD.<ref name=\"Hymnary\" /> The hymn first appeared in 1633, designated to be sung to the 1609 melody by [[Melchior Vulpius]] to the Passion hymn \"Jesu Kreuz, Leiden und Pein\". \n<!--=== Hymn texts and models ===\nIn the following table, the first column has Reusner's text taken from EG 275, the second column the texts from which he derived them, the psalm verses in the [[King James Version]] and the doxology for the seventh stanza, and finally the third column Winkworth's translation. EG 275 was modernised compared to the original at the end of the fourth stanza{{efn|1560: Wider mein feind / Der gar vil seind / An mir auff beden seiten.{{rp|24}}}} and the beginning of the seventh stanza.{{efn|1560: Glori / lob, ehr vnnd herligkeit / Sei Got Vatter vnd Son bereit / Dem heilgen Geist mit namen.{{rp|24}}}}\n{{columns|width=auto\n| col1 = Reusner<poem>\n1. In dich hab ich gehoffet, Herr;\nhilf, dass ich nicht zuschanden werd\n-->\n== Melody and musical settings ==\n[[Johann Sebastian Bach]] used three stanzas from the hymn (10, 20, and 34) as commenting chorales in his ''[[St John Passion structure|St John Passion]]''. The tenth stanza is sung as [[St John Passion structure#14|movement 14], ending Part I after [[Saint Peter|Peter]]'s denial, beginning \"{{lang|de|Petrus, der nicht denkt zur\u00fcck|italic=no}}\" (Peter, when he fails to think)\".<ref name=\"Dahn 14\" /><ref name=\"BD 14\" /> The 20th stanza follows Jesus telling his mother and [[John the Evangelist|John the disciple]] to take care of each other, beginning \"Er nahm alles wohl in acht\" (He took good care of everything) as [[St John Passion structure#28|movement 28]].<ref name=\"Dahn 28\" /><ref name=\"BD 28\" /> The final stanza, beginning \"Jesu, der du warest tot\" (Jesus who you were dead), is used as [[St John Passion structure#32|movement 32]] juxtaposed to a bass aria, after Jesus died.<ref name=\"Dahn 32\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"BD 14\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.bach-digital.de/receive/BachDigitalWork_work_00011273\n| title = Jesu Leiden, Pein und Tod BWV 245/14 ChS; BC F 115.2a/b \n| website = [[Bach Digital]]\n| date = 2018\n| accessdate = 13 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BD 28\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.bach-digital.de/receive/BachDigitalWork_work_00011276\n| title = Jesu Leiden, Pein und Tod BWV 245/28 ChS; BC F 115.3a/b \n| website = [[Bach Digital]]\n| date = 2018\n| accessdate = 13 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Dahn 14\">{{cite web\n| last = Dahn\n| first = Luke\n| url = https://www.bach-chorales.com/BWV0245_14.htm\n| title = BWV 245.14\n| website = bach-chorales.com\n| date = 2018\n| accessdate = 10 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Dahn 28\">{{cite web\n| last = Dahn\n| first = Luke\n| url = https://www.bach-chorales.com/BWV0245_28.htm\n| title = BWV 245.28\n| website = bach-chorales.com\n| date = 2018\n| accessdate = 13 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Dahn 32\">{{cite web\n| last = Dahn\n